NUMBER 355
NAME Bank of Fayd
DEEPCAVE
FIXED_LIGHT
INDOOR_FLOOR
BANK
CALL 33
*DESCRIPTION_START
Two columns of guards keep a watchful eye on you as you walk into the Bank of Fayd. A clerk indicates a sign displaying the services offered by the bank.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT O 249
ITEM 0 204
ITEM 9 693
IF ITEM9
  EQUAL ITEMBIT0 1
ENDIF
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM READ 0
Deposit cash by indicating the total amount in copper pennies.
1 Gold Crown = 10 Silver Shillings = 100 Copper Pennies.
[DEPOSIT xxx, WITHDRAW xxx]
Your BALANCE may be viewed at any time.
You may deposit to your safety deposit box for a fee of one gold crown
per deposit. There is no fee for looking at the contents of your box or
withdrawing items.
[DEPOSIT item, WITHDRAW item]
*DESCRIPTION_END
;
IFENTRY -1
  IFVAR ORG = 20
    IFVAR DISGUISED = 0
      ECHO PLAYER As you enter, a guard signals an armored enforcer in the corner.
      IFVAR MONINROOM < 3
        GENMON 321
      ENDIF
      IFVAR WARRANT < 6
        ADD WARRANT 1
      ENDIF
    ENDIF
  ENDIF
ENDIF


NUMBER 312
NAME Physicians' Guild
DEEPCAVE
FIXED_LIGHT
HEALER
CALL 33
*DESCRIPTION_START
Second in age only to the Adventurers' Guild, the Physicians' Guild seems to exude solemnity. Charts representing the anatomy's of the various races hang on all walls. The adventurers sitting and lying about the floor are being treated by Fayd's finest diagnosticians. A door leads back to the street.
*DESCRIPTION_END
EXIT N 313
EXIT W 314
ITEM 0 200 VAL2=277
ITEM 1 1416 ADJ1=355
ITEM 9 693
IF ITEM9
  EQUAL ITEMBIT0 1
ENDIF
IFPREVERB SIT -1
  IFVAR ORG = 20
    CLEARVERB
    POSITION SIT
    ECHO PLAYER The physician says "I'm sorry, you won't be getting any aid from us.  You've already given us too much business with your stupid war.
ENDIF
ENDIF
IFPREVERB LAY -1
  IFVAR ORG = 20
    CLEARVERB
    POSITION LAY
    ECHO PLAYER The physician says "I'm sorry, you won't be getting any aid from us.  You've already given us too much business with your stupid war.
  ENDIF
ENDIF
;
NUMBER 206
NAME Bazaar Center
MONSTER_GROUP 1
CALL 33
*DESCRIPTION_START
You revel in the tumult as the center of the bazaar overwhelms your senses
with its smell and sizzle of roast mutton, its cries of hawkers and cajoling
merchants. Street dancers, minstrels, and half-clad jugglers amuse the
crowds near a large marble fountain.  A large statue is almost as formidable
a presence as the fountain.
*DESCRIPTION_END
OUTDOOR_OTHER
FIXED_LIGHT
EXIT ABOVE 2152
EXIT NE 204
EXIT SE 205
EXIT E 203
EXIT N 207
EXIT S 208
EXIT W 209
EXIT NW 223
EXIT SW 224
ITEM 0 197 ADJ1=178 ADJ2=187
ITEM 1 204 ADJ1=227
ITEM 2 1416 ADJ1=355
ITEM 3 304
ITEM 4 346 ADJ1=423 ADJ2=187
ITEM 5 400 ADJ1=468
ITEM 9 693 ADJ1=10
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM READ 1
The daily water nymph show has been postponed due to lack of nymphs. Courtesy of the Fayd Chamber of Commerce.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
The fountain is quite a marvel: made of smooth blue marble streaked with white, it continuously sprays streaming water, sparkling with golden light. There is a painted sign on the fountain.
*DESCRIPTION_END
PUT 0 198 VAL2=100 VAL3=0
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 4
The proud form of a beloved King stands guard over the city he loved.
The brilliance of the statue portrays King Frederick Kentaurus the III
at the height of his power. His chiseled body is covered in a suit of
golden plate armor, with the symbol of the Kentaraus family emblazoned
across the breast plate. Strong hands easily grip the pommel of the
beautiful alyzorn weapon crafted for kings and the compassionate black
eyes seem to gaze out across the entire city, ever on guard for any
signs of trouble. A golden plaque has been imbedded at the bottom of
the statue.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAMINE 5
Highly stylized lettering flows across the face of the plaque.
*DESCRIPTION_END
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM READ 5
              KING FREDERICK KENTAURUS THE III

            "I hear his name and see his face..."

         "Caught upon the wings of the morning breeze,"
           "Carried on strands of golden sunlight,"
        "Reflected in the waters of the clear blue seas,"
       "Painted by the glittering stars in the dark night."

         "Never to be forgotten, never to be diminished."
                "Always near in heart and mind"
        "Echoing forever, down the endless halls of time."
*DESCRIPTION_END
;
IFENTRY -1
  IFVAR ORG = 20
    IFVAR DISGUISED = 0
      IFVAR WARRANT < 6
        ADD WARRANT 1
      ENDIF
      ECHO ALL A stir runs through the crowd at the arrogance of the Order of the Way.
    ENDIF
  ENDIF
ENDIF
;

